$Id$

       ``The Macro Implementation of SNOBOL4 in C'' (C-MAINBOL)
		      Installation instructions

Unix systems (or systems with POSIX shell, make and m4);
=======================================================

Compilation
-----------

In most cases all you need to type is "make".

The top level makefile will run the "configure" script to create
"config.m4", which is in turn used to create Makefile2, which is then
run, creating a test version of snobol4 (named "xsnobol4") which is
then regression tested and timed, and finally named "snobol4".

The "configure" tries to use the available C compiler which works
best.  If you wish to alter configure's decision process, you can run
it manually by typing "./configure OPTIONS" with zero or more of the
following options;

	--add-cppflags=STRING
		Add additional C preprocessor flags (ie; -DXXX) to
		compile commands
	--add-ldflags=STRING
		Add additional flags to final load command (ie; -lxxx)
	--add-objs=STRING
		Add additional object file to final load command
		(ie; for "poor mans load" functions)
	--add-opt=STRING
		Add additional optimization flags to compile commands
	--add-srcs=STRING
		Add additional source files for "make depend"
	--force-gcc
		Force use of GCC, the GNU C Compiler;
		fail if gcc not available.
	--force-memmove
		Force use of system memmove() function (if preseent)
		if no bcopy() function is available.  Otherwise the
		bcopy.c source file will be used.
	--largefile
		Force the use of defines for "large file" (64 bit offsets).
		Requires existance of fseeko() and ftello() stdio functions.
	--lp64
		Force the use of defines for LP64 (64-bit longs and
		pointers) datatype model where available.

		Under the LP64 model, SNOBOL4 INTEGERs are represented
		by C longs and REALs are represented as 64-bit C doubles.
		The LP64 model doubles the size of each SIL
		descriptor.  And while it allows larger strings (4GB
		vs. 16MB) and compound objects (128M descriptors vs.
		2M), the increased descriptor and arithmetic type
		sizes also degrade performance.

		If the underlying C compiler does not implement the
		LP64 model, this option may have disasterous results
		-- the current implementation DEPENDS on the fact that
		the C datatype used to represent integers is the same width
		as the C datatypes used to represent REALs and pointers.

		It does NOT select use of "long long" to represent
		SNOBOL4 integers, so --lp64 is useless on 32-bit systems.

		This option attempts to set native compiler options
		for LP64 environment where it's not the default.  This
		may require --no-gcc to disable selection of GNU C Compiler.
	--no-dlopen
		Disable use of Unix98 dlopen() API for dynamic LOAD() support
	--no-dynlib
		Disable use of all dynamic LOAD() support mechanisms
	--no-gcc
		Eliminate GNU C Compiler (GCC) from consideration.
	--no-largefile
		Disable automatic selection of large file support
		(see --largefile)
	--opt=STRING
		Supply C optimization flags (replacing default "-O"),
		for example; --opt=-O2
	--prefix=DIR
		Supply a directory prefix for bin/ and lib/ directories.
		Default prefix is /usr/local

Even if your system has not previously been tested (see doc/ports.doc)
configure will make a guess. If the build does not succeed, you may
want to consult doc/porting.doc (also available as html) for
information on the available options for use in creating a
system-specific config file.  If you need assistance please contact me
(phil@ultimate.com).

For information on including "external" C functions in the linked
binary see doc/load.doc.

Installation
------------

Typing "make install" will install the snobol4 binary and man page.
The snobol4 (PREFIX/bin/snobol4), library directory
(PREFIX/lib/snobol4) and man page (PREFIX/man/man1/snobol4.1).  The
default PREFIX is /usr/local, see --prefix= configure option above).

Please mail timing.out files to snobol4-timing@ultimate.com!


Non-unix systems;
================

The non-unix ports are not well tested.  Please send me any fixes you
discover!  See doc/porting.doc for details on porting C-MAINBOL.

The routines in tty.c (tty_save, tty_restore, tty_mode, tty_close) and
inet.c (tcp_open, udp_open) need to be supplied.  Dummy versions exist
in lib/dummy/tty.c and lib/dummy/inet.c.

The functions referenced from pml.h will not be loaded by the existing
command files, and will cause the link to fail.  There are three
possible solutions;

1. Add commands to build a SNOLIB library and include it in the link.

2. Compile the needed objects and add them directly to the link command.

3. Define one or more of NO_PML_(HOST|EXIT|REAL|FILE|DELETE|RENAME)
	when compiling pml.c.

The SPITBOL HOST() function simulation may call functions not
available on the target system.  Rather than adding a nest of ifdefs,
dummy versions of getenv() and system() have been provided in the
lib/dummy directory for this eventuality.  The SPITBOL EXIT()
simulation requires an execute() function to pass pass control to
another program.  A dummy version is provided in lib/dummy/execute.c.

MS-DOS using Borland C++
------------------------

Mark Emmer of Catspaw has compiled an older version of C-MAINBOL using
Borland C++.  Look in config/borland (or CONFIG\BORLAND). This port
has not been tested in some time.

VMS using DEC C
---------------

C-MAINBOL has been run on VMS (on VAXen using VAXC, and on Alphas
using DECC), and the DEC C RTL.

config/vms/descrip.mms is an MMS description file, which can be used
by typing:

	MMS/DESCRIP=[.CONFIG.VMS]DESCRIP.MMS

If using VAXC, /MACRO=(VAX_C=1) should be appended to the command line.

The VMS port uses native calls to implement TTY I/O, and supports
binary and noecho input.  TCP/IP I/O is implemented using DEC TCP/IP
Connection services for OpenVMS (formerly VAX/Ultrix connection
product) but not working.  It should be simple to use other TCP
packages, but if not, or none is available, add /MACRO=(NO_TCP=1) to
the MMS command line.

Jerry Lichter has run an older version of C-MAINBOL under VMS using
the GNU C compiler and the GNU C library.

Win32 using MicroSoft Visual C++ 5.0
------------------------------------

The Win32 port is in it's infancy.  The snobol4.exe links and passes
regression testing on WinNT 4.0, but system dependant code needs work;

*	TCP/IP I/O (using winsock32) is present, but not working.
*	Binary & noecho TTY I/O has been coded, but does not work.
*	Process timing under Win95 does not work properly (see win32/mstime.c)
*	LOAD() of DLL's implemented, but not tested
	(document how to make a .DLL)

To compile;
	nmake -f config\win32\ntmsvc.mak

Anything else
-------------

C-MAINBOL has been designed to be modular, and makes only modest
demands on the C library.  See doc/porting.doc for information.

Let me know!
============

Please let me know of your success and failures to bring up C-SNOBOL4!

Please mail timing.out files to snobol4-timing@ultimate.com along with
information on your system make, model and CPU clock speed, if known.

If you want to recieve a note when new releases are made, send mail
to c-mainbol-users-request@ultimate.com
